{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19590"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70191"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of progressive abdominal swelling. He underwent an emergency laparotomy for perforated duodenal ulcer eight months ago. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include metformin and amlodipine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a visible midline laparotomy scar with a 10 cm reducible swelling that becomes more prominent when he coughs (Image 1, 2). The surrounding skin is normal with no erythema or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rectal divarication","Paraumbilical hernia","Epigastric hernia","Incisional hernia","Omphalocele"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of incisional hernia developing through a previous surgical wound. The presence of a midline laparotomy scar and a bulge that becomes more prominent with increased intra-abdominal pressure (during coughing) are characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncisional hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in approximately 10-15% of patients following abdominal surgery and is more common after emergency operations, in patients with obesity, diabetes, or post-operative wound infections. These hernias typically develop within the first year after surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectal divarication\u003C/strong\u003E (diastasis recti) refers to separation of the rectus abdominis muscles in the midline. While this can cause abdominal bulging, it would not be localised to a surgical scar and would be more diffuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through a defect in the linea alba superior to the umbilicus but would not be associated with a surgical scar. These hernias are typically smaller and more localised to the umbilical region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpigastric hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the midline between the xiphoid process and umbilicus through a defect in the linea alba. These are typically small, often asymptomatic, and not associated with previous surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital defect where abdominal contents protrude through the umbilical ring and would not be relevant in an adult patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incisional hernias occur through previous surgical incision sites and are more common in midline laparotomy scars.","Incisional hernias typically present with a bulge that becomes more prominent with increased intra-abdominal pressure.","Risk factors for incisional hernia include obesity, wound infection, and emergency surgery."],"references":["Ortega-Deballon P, Renard Y, de Launay J, Lafon T, Roset Q, Passot G. Incidence, risk factors, and burden of incisional hernia repair after abdominal surgery in France: a nationwide study. Hernia. 2023;27(4):861-871. doi:10.1007/s10029-023-02825-9","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70191"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21633"},{"type":"media","id":"21634"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21633"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WYNDJXFtkC3omnp1htPgHqUQGlAE6H.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WYNDJXFtkC3omnp1htPgHqUQGlAE6H.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21634"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iW3pAC1uEVCqLiqcq0JVmrFtynEonc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/iW3pAC1uEVCqLiqcq0JVmrFtynEonc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70191"},"attributes":